data.reasoningText:
Now I have a good understanding of the project. Let me plan the component decomposition and then implement it.

## Component Plan: Settings Dashboard

### Component Tree
```
SettingsDashboard              (page — owns active section, all data, orchestrates layout)
├── SettingsSidebar            (vertical nav tabs, highlights active)
├── ProfileSection             (profile editing form with save/discard)
├── NotificationsSection       (toggles & muted channels list)
├── SecuritySection            (password, 2FA, sessions)
│   └── RevokeSessionDialog    (confirmation modal)
└── AppearanceSection          (theme, font, language, compact mode + preview)


```

The SettingsDashboard will manage the active section and all data state, delegating to ISettingsService for persistence, while each child section receives its data as parameters and notifies the parent when changes need saving. I'll build the components bottom-up starting with the leaf nodes, then compose them into the parent sections, and finally wire everything together in the dashboard.

I'll organize the files under Components/Pages/Settings with each component in its own Razor file alongside corresponding CSS isolation files, then update the imports.

```

razor
@page "/settings"
@using Components.Pages.Settings
@inject ISettingsService SettingsService
@inject NavigationManager Navigation

<div class="settings-container">
    <SettingsSidebar @ref="sidebar" OnSectionChange="HandleSectionChange" />
    <div class="settings-content">
        @switch(currentSection)
        {
            case "profile":
                <ProfileSection />
                break;
            case "notifications":
                <NotificationsSection />
                break;
            case "security":
                <SecuritySection />
                break;
            case "appearance":
                <AppearanceSection />
                break;
        }
    </div>
</div>

@code {
    private SettingsSidebar sidebar;
    private string currentSection = "profile";

    private void HandleSectionChange(string section)
    {
        currentSection = section;
    }
}
```

Now I'll create the sidebar component with navigation between sections, the profile section for user information updates, notifications section for email and push preferences, security section with session management and password changes, and appearance section for theme selection. Each will have its own styling file.

